    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "Consider this simple example:\r\n\r\n```\r\nGet-ItemProperty -Path 'HKLM:\\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Uninstall\\NSIS' -Name InstallLocation).InstallLocation\r\n```\r\n\r\nSince there is no `HKLM:\\` on Linux or macOS, PowerShell will report an error like this the following\r\n\r\n```\r\nGet-ItemProperty : Cannot find drive. A drive with the name 'HKLM' does not exi\r\nst.\r\n\r\nAt /Users/me/here-is-a-very-long-path-that-will-ultimately-get-wrapped-after-80-\r\n-characters/myScript.ps1:34 char:19\r\n```\r\n\r\n> Also you can do Out-File -Width\r\n\r\nI'm not looking for ways to control the output width of my scripts, but PowerShell output such as error messages.\r\n\r\n> Powershell auto detect a console width\r\n\r\nI'm using iTerm2 with `bash` as my main shell. `bash` respects my window-width for its line-breaks, it's only `powershell` that doesn't (see screenshot below!)\r\n\r\n![screen shot 2016-11-24 at 15 53 59](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1504938/20602543/173f04ac-b25e-11e6-9d0d-9fda4395485c.png)\r\n\r\nSo maybe we should refer to this as a bug instead ðŸ˜‰ ",
